{"title":"Level 5 — Tidyverse","markdown":{"headingText":"Level 5 — Tidyverse","headingAttr":{"id":"","classes":["unnumbered"],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-problem}\n**Where this level is headed**\n\nBase R can do everything you've done through Level 4 — but reread some of that code: `participants[participants$age >= 65 & participants$systolic_bp >= 130, ]`. It works, but it doesn't read like the question you're actually asking. The tidyverse — `dplyr` especially — lets you write \"take the data, filter to seniors with elevated blood pressure, group by county, summarise the mean\" almost exactly as you'd say it out loud.\n:::\n\n## What you'll build toward\n\nBy the end of this level you'll rewrite nearly everything from Level 4 more readably: selecting and filtering with `select()` and `filter()`, sorting with `arrange()`, building and summarizing variables with `mutate()` and `summarise()`, grouped analysis with `group_by()`, quick counts and unique values with `count()` and `distinct()`, tidyverse-style renaming, applying one operation across many columns with `across()`, and chaining every one of these together with the native pipe `|>` into a single, readable pipeline.\n\n## Topics in this level\n\n- `select()`, `filter()`, `arrange()`\n- `mutate()` and `summarise()`\n- `group_by()`, `count()`, `distinct()`\n- `rename()` and `across()`\n- The native pipe `|>`\n- Chaining multi-step analyses\n\n## A preview mission\n\nYour mission across this level: your professor asks you to identify every participant 65 or older with elevated blood pressure — in one readable pipeline, not a maze of nested brackets and repeated `df$` references.\n\nBy the last page, you'll write a single chained pipeline — import, filter, group, summarise, arrange — that reads, top to bottom, almost exactly like the research question it answers.\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-